flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn live platform behavior into trustworthy operator visibility and drift-attestation truth"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than run reconstruction, governance closure, and final-verdict publication"]
    G3["Answer whether operators can see the right runtime surfaces, detect drift before false certification, and trust that visible green belongs to the active path"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not that some logs exist"]
    E2["The entry is a working platform with a declared active runtime path, the real runtime surfaces that path uses, and observability plus control scope ready to attest those same surfaces live"]
    E3["The final-phase telemetry plan already assumes this proof runs on top of the working platform"]
    E4["The broader design authority pins one active runtime path per phase, records it in run-control evidence, and forbids in-phase path switching"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Declared active runtime path plus live telemetry, traces, and logs from those same surfaces"]
    R2["Freshness, alert, drift, and handle checks"]
    R3["Observability attestation truth for the run"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Run-scoped correlation fields"]
    C2["Telemetry from the actual active runtime surfaces"]
    C3["Dashboard and alarm state"]
    C4["Handle-resolution state for the active path"]
    C5["Durable attestation artifacts such as correlation audits or freshness and coverage checks"]
    C6["OpenTelemetry enablement, pinned correlation mode, required correlation fields, correlation-audit surface, and named dashboards and alarms for platform ops, cost guardrails, error rate, RTDL lag, and ingress HTTP anomaly"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats runtime execution truth and runtime visibility truth as two different boundaries"]
    L2["The system is not saying because the platform is running, operators must be able to see it correctly"]
    L3["It is saying there is a dedicated boundary where freshness, alert coverage, drift visibility, correlation continuity, and active-path fidelity have to be proven as their own truth"]
    L4["That is a much more serious operational posture than simply having metrics present"]
    L5["This is strong A-level design signal because truthful live visibility has an explicit owner and closure object"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The path is materially seated in the current wired platform"]
    S2["The handles registry pins the platform log-group namespace, collector surface, primary metrics and log exporter, required correlation headers and fields, correlation-audit surface, dashboards, and critical alarms"]
    S3["The implementation trail shows this was treated as an executed proof boundary rather than static config"]
    S4["The earlier observability proof lane explicitly probed the ingress edge, orchestrator surface, stream-lane telemetry surface, and observability lane"]
    S5["It failed closed when ingress correlation-carriage proof and telemetry proof were insufficient, and the fix was repinned to emit structured correlation evidence before rerunning green"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform refuses two weak shortcuts: dashboards as proxy for trustworthy observability, and stale or partial telemetry as proxy for active-path truth"]
    Y2["The operations, governance, and meta readiness definition says this plane is not production-ready merely because dashboards, receipts, budgets, or teardown workflows exist"]
    Y3["The platform must show observability is usable for diagnosis and prevention, drift is visible, and hidden operational shortcuts are not accepted"]
    Y4["The earlier observability implementation history reinforces that intent"]
    Y5["When the live ingress boundary lacked correlation-carriage proof, the answer was not to relax the gate but to remediate the runtime boundary and rerun the proof"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The operations, governance, and meta metric contract defines closure criteria: metric freshness, critical alert coverage, placeholder-handle count, required-handle resolution, and drift-detection success"]
    X2["The final-phase telemetry plan defines how those criteria are observed: dashboard freshness, alert fire and clear counts, active drift checks on the same runtime surfaces, and fail-fast on drift between live runtime and declared active path"]
    X3["The design authority pins OpenTelemetry-first, run-scoped correlation continuity across edge, stream processors, orchestrators, custom runtimes, and evidence writers, with fail-closed closure if required correlation fields are missing"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds another formal boundary on top of already-running lanes"]
    T2["That costs more instrumentation, explicit correlation propagation, dashboard and alert validation, freshness checks, active-path drift checks, and handle and secret attestation for the runtime actually in use"]
    T3["But that cost buys the ability to answer whether operators had truthful live view of what ran, whether alerts covered the right failure families, and whether the green-looking system was actually the declared active path rather than stale or wrong surface"]
    T4["That is why the final-phase plan treats drift visibility before certification as a qualitative proof objective instead of leaving it implicit"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still execute lanes, append governance facts, publish final verdict, and maybe even tear down safely"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to whether the metrics were fresh"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to whether alarms covered real critical failures"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to whether the active runtime path matched the observed surfaces"]
    N5["It loses a clean answer to whether handles and secrets on the live path were actually resolved"]
    N6["It loses a clean answer to whether operators could have detected drift before falsely certifying the run"]
    N7["That would weaken A immediately because the platform would run and report but have no explicit owner for truthful live visibility and drift attestation"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Metric freshness is within budget"]
    O2["Critical alert coverage exists for declared failure families"]
    O3["Placeholder-handle count in the active runtime path is zero, required handle and secret resolution succeeds, and drift between live runtime and declared active path is visible rather than hidden"]
    O4["Owned outcome: observability attestation truth that the active runtime path is visible, fresh, attributable, and drift-checked enough to support safe certification"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for turning live platform behavior into trustworthy operator visibility rather than treating observability as decoration"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>freshness, alert coverage, drift visibility, correlation continuity, and active-path fidelity are designed proof objects, not dashboard side effects"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>this boundary is concretely seated in pinned observability handles, dashboards, alarms, correlation fields, and the already-executed observability proof lane"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>this path is governed by metric freshness, critical alert coverage, required-handle resolution, placeholder-handle elimination, active-path drift checks, and fail-closed correlation continuity"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the platform already knows visible green can be false if it comes from stale or wrong surfaces, which is why the path insists on active-path fidelity and drift detection before certification"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>the platform can prove truthful live visibility as its own operational truth instead of assuming that a running system is automatically a visible and governable one"]
  end

